data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 10, the Cosmos DB provider already threw `InvalidOperationException` on sync LINQ by default, but you could opt in to **sync-over-async** (e.g., via `ConfigureWarnings` to suppress `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported`).

**In EF Core 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All four of your sync calls — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no workaround.

### The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods become `async` and use `await`
- Sync operators → async equivalents (`ToListAsync`, `FirstAsync`, `CountAsync`, `SaveChangesAsync`)
- Convention: suffix method names with `Async`

This will ripple up through your call chain — every caller must also become async, up to the controller actions (which ASP.NET Core already supports natively via `async Task<IActionResult>`).
